From 106e863d8eefd80f9f8ebe205d70fdb02a27d6ed Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: vllm-shim <vllm-shim@local>
Date: Thu, 1 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 4/5] debug(quark): add MXFP4 Triton-vs-reference verification
 harness

The MoRI EP MXFP4 Triton 2-stage chain (introduced by the preceding
quark/mori patches) has no end-to-end correctness test in AITER:
fused_moe_mxfp4_silu and fused_moe_mxfp4 each have per-kernel tests,
but their chained use (silu output feeding the W2 GEMM as A) is novel
to this patch stack. A live deployment reported coherent-shaped but
semantically random output (multilingual token salad, no natural stop),
which is the signature of a systematic but localized math bug in the
chain.

Static analysis ruled out the call-arg semantics: expert_mask polarity,
align_experts = expert_mask.numel(), num_local_tokens scalar handling,
weight/scale strides, swizzle_mx_b=False matching skipped e8m0_shuffle,
and the sentinel-position contamination bound (writes to one position
per call, multiplied by sorted_weights[sentinel]=0 in stage2, then
zero-summed). None of those explains the observed magnitude of error.

Without GPU access on the dev box, the next debug step is to compare
the Triton output against a pure-torch reference of the same math and
have the deployment dump the first divergent rows. The reference and
the verify scaffold are wired in here. Off by default; opt in with
VLLM_SHIM_MXFP4_VERIFY=1.

triton_mxfp4_reference.py: fp32 dequant via OCP MXFP4 LUT + E8M0
scale broadcast, then the same x @ W13.T -> chunk -> silu*up -> @ W2.T
-> weighted-sum chain in Python. Slow on purpose; cached per-expert
dequant keeps it tractable for the first ~32 rows of one warmup batch.

triton_mxfp4_dispatch.py: gates on VLLM_SHIM_MXFP4_VERIFY, skips when
torch.cuda.is_current_stream_capturing() is true (SGLang's warmup runs
eager before capture, so verification fires there and not inside a
graph), and runs once per unique shape key. On mismatch, logs the
first three divergent rows with their topk_ids and topk_weights so
the distribution of failures across (token, expert) pairs is visible
in stderr.

Knobs:
  VLLM_SHIM_MXFP4_VERIFY=1            enable
  VLLM_SHIM_MXFP4_VERIFY_ATOL=0.5     fail threshold (bf16 MoE noise)
  VLLM_SHIM_MXFP4_VERIFY_MAX_ROWS=32  per-key row cap for the slow loop
